Nice vegan Indian food restaurant with an all-you-can-eat set menu. I have eaten here many times for lunch, and I always enjoy it. The food is delicious. The ambience is nice too - a chill, relaxed vibe, nice decorations and classic Indian tunes make place feel homey and healthy, like a refuge from the city and a great setting for a nourishing meal.  The set menu usually includes one vegetable dish, one legume and one soy protein (faux meat), along with salad, brown rice, naan, pakora, raita, and mint-coconut and tamarind chutneys. If you want more of any dish you just ask the server and they bring you another. The three main dishes come with a variety of seasonings and perhaps a sauce. At the end they bring a little dessert, which is always delicious.  Service is good and attentive. If you have an allergy or other dietary restriction, they will listen and try to accommodate you. I once declined a dessert containing bulgar wheat for this reason, and the server kindly, and unexpectedly, brought me a different one.  The price is quite reasonable for a well-prepared and filling lunch.

A friend suggested this place for dinner before a show, and I was instantly excited when I found out its concept. Roughly $15 for dinner (and $10 for lunch), you can apparently eat as much of their fixed menu as you want, although one serving of everything (minus a couple things I couldn't eat) was still more than enough to make me leave there stuffed!  And it is all vegetarian - actually mostly vegan. A couple of the items contain dairy. And the meal consists of six tastes: salty, sweet, sour, bitter, astringent and pungent.  The evening we went, they had yellow dal, Sarson Ka Saag (mustard greens), a fresh salad, raita, and a mushroom & bean dish that I don't know the name of as the main entrees. You get a small dish of each of these along with your rice (you get to choose white or brown rice), and a chickpea fritter. And before your meal, you get Papadum with chutneys. And after the meal, you get a small dessert. My friend who is neither vegan nor gluten-free got Gulab Jamun (the milky doughnut-like balls covered in syrup), and I got Besan Burfi, which was delicious.  The staff is great at accommodating dietary restrictions, but it's probably best to tell them right from the beginning. Our server asked us whether we wanted brown or white rice, but I didn't know if she was going to come back to ask about dietary restrictions or anything, so I didn't know when was the best time to mention my being vegan and gluten-free. And I didn't get a chance to until after our food was brought to us, and when I did, she took away the raita and mentioned that the green chutney has yogurt in it. And the bread (which I think was more of a roti than naan) apparently had olive oil instead of ghee, but it was a wheat flour-based bread so I still couldn't eat it. But thankfully we had plenty of papadum, and they brought out a second helping when we went through the first.  I definitely want to come back and eat here again - even if it might be a little out of my way!
